<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Recently described from the southern Carpathians in Romania from a single collection. The two Greenland collections are the first recorded since the type has been published. Both are from the High Arctic zone in Greenland at 70° and 74°N, and it is thus in the northernmost group among the 28 Greenland species. The records are the first from North America and the first outside Europe.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Only two records, both most likely with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix arctica" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="arctica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix arctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and both on calcareous soil. The only previous collection, the type, grew with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. retusa" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="retusa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. retusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. at 2270 m a.s.l. in the Carpathians (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/15-097" author="Eberhardt, U" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1285 - 1303" refId="B11" refString="Eberhardt, U, Ronikier, A, Schuetz, N, Beker, HJ, 2015a. The genus Hebeloma in the alpine belt of the Carpathians including two new species. Mycologia 107: 1285 - 1303, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/15-097" title="The genus Hebeloma in the alpine belt of the Carpathians including two new species." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/15-097" volume="107" year="2015 a">Eberhardt et al. 2015a</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995425518050086" author="Shiryaev, AG" journalOrPublisher="Contemporary Problems of Ecology" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="458 - 471" refId="B44" refString="Shiryaev, AG, Zmitrovich, IV, Ezhov, ON, 2018. Taxonomic and ecological structure of basidial macromycetes biota in polar deserts of the northern hemisphere. Contemporary Problems of Ecology 11: 458 - 471, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995425518050086" title="Taxonomic and ecological structure of basidial macromycetes biota in polar deserts of the northern hemisphere." url="https://doi.org/10.1134/S1995425518050086" volume="11" year="2018">Shiryaev et al. (2018)</bibRefCitation>
reported from 
<bibRefCitation author="Zmitrovich, IV" editor="Matveeva, NV" journalOrPublisher="Marafon, St. Petersburg" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="211 - 225" refId="B54" refString="Zmitrovich, IV, Ezhov, ON, 2015. Agaricoid fungi (Basidiomycota, Agaricomycetes). In: Matveeva, NV, Ed., Rasteniya i griby polyarnykh pustyn' severnogo polushariya (The Plants andFungi of Polar Deserts of Northern Hemisphere). Marafon, St. Petersburg: 211 - 225" title="Agaricoid fungi (Basidiomycota, Agaricomycetes)." volumeTitle="Rasteniya i griby polyarnykh pustyn' severnogo polushariya (The Plants andFungi of Polar Deserts of Northern Hemisphere)." year="2015">Zmitrovich and Ezhov (2015)</bibRefCitation>
the presence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Groger &amp; Zschieschang" authorityYear="1981" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma gigaspermum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="gigaspermum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma gigaspermum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gröger">Groeger</normalizedToken>
&amp; Zschiesch. from Franz Josefs Land (Russia). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Beker, HJ" journalOrPublisher="Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" refId="B4" refString="Beker, HJ, Eberhardt, U, Vesterholt, J, 2016. Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm. Fungi Europaei Edizioni Tecnografica, Lomazzo" title="Hebeloma (Fr.) P. Kumm." year="2016">Beker et al. (2016)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. gigaspermum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="gigaspermum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. gigaspermum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most likely a synonym of 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. nauseosum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="nauseosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. nauseosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Sacc. Since neither 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. nauseosum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="nauseosum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. nauseosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nor any other species of 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. subsp. sect." order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="section" section="Sacchariolentia" species="nauseosum" subSpecies="sect.">H. sect. Sacchariolentia</taxonomicName>
occurs in arctic areas, it may be that the large spores and the occurrence in the High Arctic zone rather point to 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. grandisporum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="grandisporum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. grandisporum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Beker, U. Eberh. &amp; A. Ronikier; Eberhardt, Ronikier, Schuetz &amp; Beker, Mycologia 107 (6): 1293" authorityYear="2015" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma grandisporum" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="grandisporum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma grandisporum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of the most easily recognized among the arctic-alpine 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the small basidiomes, the large spores, the relatively few, distant lamellae and large, 2-spored basidia. To date, it is the only 
<taxonomicName class="Agaricomycetes" family="Hymenogastraceae" genus="Hebeloma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Hebeloma" order="Ostropales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Hebeloma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, of which we are aware, that has consistently 2-spored basidia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
